L. simplex Boxshall, 2000
from deep-water arrowtooth eel in the eastern North Atlantic (
). Despite the fact that synaphobranchid eels including the above four host species are widely distributed in the world’s oceans, especially on the continental slopes (
), little is known about the biology of
Lophoura
copepods infecting those eels. This is because deep-sea fishes are usually not captured in commercial fisheries and there are few scientists working on the parasites of the deep-sea fishes. Actually, the type specimens of
L. cornuta
and
L. gracilis
were collected on board the U.S. Bureau of Fisheries steamer Albatross in 1906 and 1882, respectively (
), and that of
L. simplex
